The two Poland
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to deprive Bronisław Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former Minister for Foreign Affairs - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another new declaration stating that he was not an agent of the secret police during communism.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's behavior, and Geremek stated that the lustration law poses a threat to public liberties.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jarosław Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of fostering anti-Polish sentiments.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision dated May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament for now.
But this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government whose sole purpose is to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best within him, while the second liberates the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarztwo followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when martial law was decreed in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika."
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of communist dictatorship throughout the entire Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a divided country between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes of government, but the country has remained stable. Even the former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seeking factions, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and antisemitic groups, heirs of pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethnic-clerical fundamentalism.
We see worrying signs everywhere: the authority of the Justice Ministry is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is questioned, officials are bought off, and the role of the prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also increased crime, a market economy along with the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by growing income inequality.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also instilled fear of foreigners and fear of a mass Western cultural invasion.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but it took care of them.
In a world of freedom, no one takes care of us.
This is in the atmosphere of anxiety that the ruling coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
The Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the pinnacle.
But the guilty among the communists have not been punished and the virtuous Solidarity activists have not been rewarded.
Also, a sense of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed against both former enemies and old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest achievement in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland needed a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes went unpunished, virtue was rewarded, and injustices were righted.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the losing political parties chose a method: a major purge.
According to initial estimates, lustration is expected to take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the security service archives; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised to undergo lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and prohibited from practicing their profession for ten years.
