The cardinal Dziwisz of Krakow reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity, and unfounded accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, whether proven or not, to have belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of either NATO or the European Union.
Today, two Polands are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge fights against the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - one of openness and tolerance, the Poland of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends from the underground and prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The constitutional court's decision leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will neither destroy what gave birth to it, the desire for freedom, nor what it has produced, a democratic state.
